author: 春長
text: What kind of coding is it that allow you to get to that result？

author: Gustavo Yamamoto
text:
@春長 
3 = さ
4 = よ
5 = う
7 = な
0 = ら
さようなら, it reads "sayōnara".
Meaning, "Goodbye".
 It's the way of reading of each number. for example, number three in Japanese it is read
as "san" (さん) which means that, if you take the first letter, you can read as "Sa." but there's an other way to read it. is "mi" from "mittsu" (三つ - three when counting something). that aplies to almost every letter in Japanese of hiragana.

author: Gustavo Yamamoto
text:
the only problem is, if there's consecutive numbers like, this:
3 3 3 (misami,sasami,misasa,etc.)
you'll have to try every kind of reading pattern possible XD

author: シュウヘイ
text: 無線呼び出し（むせんよびだし）は、特定の手順によって、電波で小型受信機（通信機器）に合図を送るシステムである。主に連絡を取りたい相手の通信機器に情報を知らせるために用いる。日本ではポケットベル、または略してポケベルと呼ばれる。最盛期を迎えた1990年代（平成）の流行期には個人需要が高く、若者ユーザーからは更に省略され、ベルの愛称で呼ばれた。

author: Gustavo Yamamoto
text:
that code means "goodbye"
3 = さ
4 = よ
5 = う
7 = な
0 = ら
さようなら, it reads "sayōnara".
Meaning, "Goodbye".

author: John Doe
text: @Gustavo Yamamoto  Japanese really has a lot of pun/word-play potential huh

author: Gustavo Yamamoto
text:
@John Doe  yeah, it does...
that one made me think for 30 minutes to understand cause I don't know Japanese that much

author: Forde
text: @Gustavo Yamamoto  how is 5 = うand 0 = ら?

author: Gustavo Yamamoto
text:
@Forde  The う(u) for 5, is because it sounds like five in Chinese (wu).
The ら(ra) for 0, is because its sound is closer to the sound of れ(re). But you're may thinking, "but, why 0 is れ (re)?"
The reason for that is simple, 
0 in Japanese has two different ways to read:
- ゼロ (zero)
- れい (rei)
and then,  れ is 0,
resulting to 0 = ら.

author: Daniel Lye
text: @Peter Griffin  As Emi Boquin has mentioned, ARGs are Alternate Reality Games, and they often come in the form of seemingly innocent pictures or videos that hide a cryptic puzzle or clue within. The charm of ARGs is in not knowing that it’s a game (imo) and just being immersed in the lore and atmosphere.

author: Select2Play
text:
@Hikaru Hakkotsu  no, not like squid game. An ARG would be when someone starts posting cryptic messages on the internet through social media that when deciphered takes the person somewhere and slowly builds a story. We have a ton of those on YouTube, it's pretty fun.

To put it simply its just a string of puzzles that you can stumble on around the internet that are disguised as something real.

text:
ねるねるが言いたいことを簡潔に纏めてみるよ？

ね「は？これが可愛いか？どこがだよ？面白くねーだろ？」
ファン「あらし乙！お前キモい消えろ」
ね「だって可愛いでごり押してんじゃん！」
俺「え？(結局可愛いと思ってんのかよこいつ)」
ファン「荒し消えろ！！」
